</head>

@GRMIDX{{index="Giving and Receiving" grammar="Giving and Receiving"}}
@GRMIDX{{index="@HI{{ageru}}" grammar="@HI{{ageru}}" anchor="ageru"}}
@GRMIDX{{index="@HI{{sashiageru}}" grammar="@HI{{sashiageru}}" anchor="sashiageru"}}
@GRMIDX{{index="@HI{{yaru}}" grammar="@HI{{yaru}}" anchor="yaru"}}
@GRMIDX{{index="@HI{{morau}}" grammar="@HI{{morau}}" anchor="morau"}}
@GRMIDX{{index="@HI{{itadaku}}" grammar="@HI{{itadaku}}" anchor="itadaku"}}
@GRMIDX{{index="@HI{{kureru}}" grammar="@HI{{kureru}}" anchor="kureru"}}
@GRMIDX{{index="@HI{{kudasaru}}" grammar="@HI{{kudasaru}}" anchor="kudasaru"}}
<body>

<h1>Giving and Receiving</h1>

<h2> Formation </h2>


<dl>
<dt>(A) A person the speaker considers to be @KT{{soto}} is given something:
<li><em>giver</em> @HI{{ha}} <em>receiver (@KT{{soto}})</em> @HI{{ni}}@N1{{}}@HI{{wo}}@HI{{@EM{{sashiageru}}}} <em>&starf;</em>
<li><em>giver</em> @HI{{ha}} <em>receiver (@KT{{soto}})</em> @HI{{ni}}@N1{{}}@HI{{wo}}@HI{{@EM{{ageru}}}}
<li><em>giver</em> @HI{{ha}} <em>receiver</em>               @HI{{ni}}@N1{{}}@HI{{wo}}@HI{{@EM{{yaru}}}}
<p></p>
<dt>(B) The speaker or a person the speaker considers to be @KT{{uchi}} receives something:
<li><em>receiver (@KT{{uchi}}) </em> @HI{{ha}} <em>giver</em> @HI{{ni}}@N1{{}}@HI{{wo}}@HI{{@EM{{itadaku}}}} <em>&#x203B;</em>
<li><em>receiver (@KT{{uchi}}) </em> @HI{{ha}} <em>giver</em> @HI{{ni}}@N1{{}}@HI{{wo}}@HI{{@EM{{morau}}}}
<p></p>
<dt>(C) A person the speaker considers to be @KT{{uchi}} is given something:
<li><em>giver (@KT{{uchi}})</em> @HI{{ha}} <em>receiver</em> @HI{{ni}}@N1{{}}@HI{{wo}}@HI{{@EM{{kudasaru}}}} <em>&#x203B;</em>
<li><em>giver (@KT{{uchi}})</em> @HI{{ha}} <em>receiver</em> @HI{{ni}}@N1{{}}@HI{{wo}}@HI{{@EM{{kureru}}}}

<p>
&starf; @HI{{sashiageru}} is the humble form of @HI{{ageru}} and is used when showing respect to the receiver.
</p>
<p>
&#x203B; humble form used to show respect to the other party
</p>

<h2> Definition </h2>

@BGRNDSTART{{}}

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
<a name="ageru">@HI{{@EM{{ageru}}}}</a> is used when something is given to someone not
part of the speaker's in-group. The giver is the subject and the receiver is marked with @HI{{ni}}.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{mountain^rice*field}}sannha@KJ{{tree^town}}sannni@KJ{{flower}}wo@EM{{agemashita}}.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Mr. Yamada gave flowers to Ms. Kimura.
  </td> </tr>
</table>      
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
<a name="sashiageru">@HI{{@EM{{sashiageru}}}}</a> is the humble form of @HI{{ageru}} and is used to show respect to the receiver. The degree of politeness is higher
than with @HI{{kudasaru}} and @HI{{itadaku}}.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{private}}ha@KJ{{before^life}}ni@KJ{{book}}wo@EM{{sashiagemashita}}.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I gave my teacher a book.
  </td> </tr>
</table>      
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
<a name="yaru">@HI{{@EM{{yaru}}}}</a> is used when the giver is in a higher position than the receiver or when the receiver is a person close to the speaker.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{private}}ha@KJ{{dog}}niesawo@EM{{yarimashita}}.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I gave some food to the dog.
  </td> </tr>
</table>      
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
<a name="morau">@HI{{@EM{{morau}}}}</a> is used when the speaker, or someone with whom the speaker empathises, receives something from someone the speaker considers to
be @KT{{soto}}. The receiver is the subject and the giver is marked with @HI{{ni}} (or sometimes with @HI{{kara}}).

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{tree^town}}sannha@KJ{{mountain^rice*field}}ni@KJ{{flower}}womoraimashita.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Ms. Kimura received flowers from Mr. Yamada.
  </td> </tr>
</table>      
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
<a name="itadaku">@HI{{@EM{{itadaku}}}}</a> is the humble polite version of @HI{{morau}} used to show respect to the giver.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{private}}ha@KJ{{section^long}}nio@KJ{{soil^products}}woitadakimashita.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I received a souvenir from the general manager.
  </td> </tr>
</table>      
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
<a name="kureru">@HI{{@EM{{kureru}}}}</a> is used when the speaker, or someone with whom the speaker empathises, is given something by someone else.
The giver is the subject and the receiver is marked by @HI{{ni}}.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{assistant^wisteria}}sannha@KJ{{younger*sister}}nio@KJ{{confectionary^child}}kuremashita.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Ms. Sato gave sweets to my younger sister.
  </td> </tr>
</table>      
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
<a name="kudasaru">@HI{{@EM{{kudasaru}}}}</a> is the honorific polite version of @HI{{morau}} used to show respect to the giver.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{section^long}}ga@KJ{{private}}nio@KJ{{soil^products}}wokudasaimashita.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      The general manager gave me a souvenir.
  </td> </tr>
</table>      
</p>

@BGRNDEND{{}}

<h2> Notes </h2>

<p>
@HI{{@EM{{ageru}}}} requires the speaker's point of view or a neutral point of view, so if the recipient is the speaker or
part of the speaker's in-group (@KT{{uchi}}) then a conflict arises and the sentence is ungrammatical.
</p>

<p>
@HI{{@EM{{morau}}}} requires the receiver's point of view. So if the giver is the speaker, a conflict arises. Therefore @HI{{@EM{{morau}}}} is only
used if the giver is not the speaker or part of the speaker's in-group. In the event that the giver is an organisation, @HI{{kara}} is
more likely to be used than @HI{{ni}}.
</p>

<p>
@HI{{@EM{{kureru}}}} is only used when the receiver is the speaker or someone with whom the speaker empathises. It cannot be used when the
giver is the speaker or someone with whom the speaker empathises, even if the receiver is also such a person; in this case @HI{{@EM{{ageru}}}}
must be used.
</p>

